         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">15/12/76 ¶  ¶ It would be interesting, dear Dr Woolls, if the supposed poisonous properties of Craspedia could be really proved. ¶  ¶ I am astonished how any professional man can advance such absurdit...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.12.15</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Woolls</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML DOC 3229, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">15/12/76</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It would be interesting, dear Dr Woolls, if the supposed poisonous properties of <name key="Craspedia">Craspedia</name> could be really proved.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am astonished how any professional man can advance such absurdities about forests, such as I have lately read.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A lecture by W. B. Clarke in which he advocated better conservation of forests, published in the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Sydney morning herald</seg> on 4 November 1876, attracted fierce criticism from L. Fane de Salis, MLC, and a controversy in the pages of the newspaper ensued.</p>
               </note> Surely water may fill a river from rain yet, but what good does it <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">there</hi>
               </seg> as we have no means to bring it up to tops of hills to serve irrigation by gravitation.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Indeed the water is lost by being swallowed up by the ocean, while trees would have kept much of it and cooled by evaporation the air and generated new clouds, such as you see hang about forests. I hope our rev. friend<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">W. B. Clarke.</p>
               </note> will read once more my "Forest-lecture".<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B71.13.03.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I was not aware that Mr Fairfax was here until after he had left.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">John Fairfax arrived in Melbourne on 19 November (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 21 November 1876, p. 4) and left on 9 December (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 11 December 1876, p. 4).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
